# Caryatid Performance Test Constitution

## Project Principles

### 1. Performance First
- All performance tests must provide accurate, reproducible metrics
- Tests must measure real-world scenarios, not artificial benchmarks
- Performance degradation must be detectable and measurable

### 2. Framework Integration
- Tests must integrate seamlessly with the existing Caryatid framework
- Reuse existing modules and patterns where possible
- Follow the pub/sub message-passing architecture

### 3. Observability
- All tests must provide clear, actionable metrics
- Include throughput (messages/sec), latency (avg/p50/p95/p99), and resource usage
- Provide statistical significance indicators

### 4. Flexibility
- Support testing both in-memory and external bus configurations
- Allow parameterization of test scenarios (message size, thread count, duration)
- Enable comparison across different configurations

## Development Standards

### Code Quality
- Maintain consistency with existing Caryatid code style
- Use Rust best practices (error handling, async/await, type safety)
- Document all configuration options
- Code must pass clippy checks
- Code should be formatted with rust-analyzer

### Testing Strategy
- Performance tests should be runnable in CI/CD environments
- Provide both quick smoke tests and comprehensive performance suites
- Include baseline measurements for regression detection

### Configuration Management
- Use TOML configuration files following Caryatid patterns
- Support environment variable overrides
- Provide sensible defaults

## Constraints

### Technical Requirements
- Rust 2021 edition
- Must use Tokio async runtime (matching Caryatid)
- Compatible with existing message bus abstractions

### Resource Considerations
- Tests should complete in reasonable time (< 5 minutes for standard suite)
- Memory usage should be bounded and predictable
- Support both single-machine and distributed testing scenarios

### Dependencies
- Minimize external dependencies beyond Caryatid's existing stack
- Use only well-maintained, production-ready crates
- Avoid dependencies that require specific OS features when possible
